Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass** that saves/restores your ViewModel state:

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _viewModel;

    public AppWindow(Page page, NoteViewModel viewModel) : base(page)
    {
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        _viewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`:**

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _viewModel;

    public App(NoteViewModel viewModel)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell(), _viewModel);
}
```

**3. Restore on first launch too** (in the ViewModel constructor):

```csharp
public class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    private string _draftText = string.Empty;

    public NoteViewModel()
    {
        // Restore any draft from a previous session
        _draftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    public string DraftText
    {
        get => _draftText;
        set => SetProperty(ref _draftText, value);
    }
}
```

### Key things to know

| Point | Why |
|---|---|
| Save in **`OnStopped`** | Fires when the app is fully backgrounded |
| Also save in **`OnDestroying`** | Android's back button can skip `Stopped` |
| **Don't** save in `OnDeactivated` | That fires for dialogs/split-screen — too noisy |
| `Resumed` **won't** fire on first launch | Initial sequence is `Created` → `Activated`, so restore in the constructor too |
| Keep handlers **fast** (<1–2 s) | Android ANR timeout is ~5 s; iOS has a similar watchdog |

`Preferences` is ideal here since draft text is a small string. For larger data, serialize to a file instead.
